Given an array with n integers, write a function to check if it could become non-decreasing by modifying at most 1 element.

An array is non-decreasing if array[i] <= array[i + 1] holds for every i (1 <= i < n). Note n belongs to [1, 10,000].

Example 1:

Input: [9,2,3,5,7]
Output: True
Explanation: You could modify the first element 9 to be 1 to get a non-decreasing array.
Example 2:

Input: [9,7,6,3,2]
Output: False
Explanation: You can't get a non-decreasing array by modify at most one element.


public static boolean checkPossibility(int[] nums) {
    int count = 0;
    for(int i = 0; i < nums.length-1; i++) {	
        if(nums[i] > nums[i+1]) {   
            if (i > 0) {
                if (nums[i-1] <= nums[i+1]) {
                    nums[i] = nums[i-1];
                } else {
                    nums[i+1] = nums[i];
                }
            }
            count++;
            if (count > 1) {
                return false;
            }
        }
    }
    return true;
}
